06652nam a22009975i 9783110790368DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107903687 a10.1515/97831107903682doi  a(DE-B1597)623861  a(OCoLC)1336406383  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP130.52.M628bW67 2022 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a306.440956223/eng/2022072600aWord Order Variation :bSemitic, Turkic and Indo-European Languages in Contact /ced. by Hiwa Asadpour, Thomas Jügel. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VIII, 269 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudia Typologica [STTYP] : Beihefte / Supplements STUF - Sprachtypologie und Universalienforschung / Language Typology and Universals ,x1617-2957 ;v3100tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tFactors influencing word ordering -- tProximal to distal: Information flow and order in Maa -- tWord order variation in Middle Iranic: Persian, Parthian, Bactrian, and Sogdian -- tWord order in Mukri Kurdish – the case of incorporated Targets -- tTargets and other postverbal arguments in Southern Balochi: A multidimensional cline -- tWord order in contact and the expression of Target in Northern Domari -- tThe evolution of VO and OV alternation in Romeyka -- tWord order in Iran-Turkic -- tWord order variation in Chulym Turkic of Siberia -- tCopulas and Target phrase positioning in the Arabic dialects of Kurdistan -- tWord order typology in North-Eastern Neo- Aramaic -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Languages -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the Iranic-Semitic-Turkic contact area, where many languages are described as verb-final, ‘Targets’ (Goals, Recipients, etc.) tend to appear in the immediate postverbal position, a pattern violating the alleged ‘basic word order’. Investigating empirical material, the present volume examines the idea of its contact-induced origin by combining various languages from inside and outside this contact area: the Greek variety Romeyka; Indic Domari; Iranic Balochi, Kurdish, Middle Persian, Parthian, Bactrian and Sogdian; Nilotic Maa; Semitic Arabic and Aramaic; Siberian and Iran-Turkic. The contributors investigate word order variation of transitive, ditransitive, and copula structures as well as intransitives with Targets. Their analyses highlight the relevance of grammatical, discourse-pragmatic, and cognitive principles. The volume highlights the importance of Target structures for linguistic theory by offering new perspectives and will be of interest to typologists and linguists interested in word order variation and information structure.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxWord order. 0aLanguages in contactzMiddle East. 0aTypology (Linguistics). 4aIndo-Europäisch. 4aSemitische Sprachen. 4aSprachkontakt. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aIndo-European, Language Contact, Semitic, Target, Turkic, Word Order.1 aAsadpour, Hiwa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsadpour, Hiwa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBirnstiel, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBulut, Christiane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerin, Bruno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJügel, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJügel, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKorn, Agnes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/